The play , “Public Obscenities", at @sohorep is a magnificent work of art. 

It is amazing when a piece of theater can transport you to your childhood as well as resonate so deeply with you as an adult.

The language of the play was an effortless mixture of Bengali (my mother tongue) & English. It was so gorgeously authentic, it literally felt symphonic to my Diasporic ears. 

I have never felt that way in a Kolkata theater or in an American theater because it had never been done. 

Thank you @mishachowdhury & the whole team, for expanding the lens of American Theater & Global Theater. Thank you for representing us. Thank you for beautifully bridging so many worlds.

This is truly a groundbreaking theatrical experience. 

Do not miss it!

#AMustWatch #PublicObscenities #SohoRep #RepresentationMatters #Bengali #GlobalNomad

Robert Brustein (April 21, 1927 – October 29, 2023).
Theater Maker. Game Changer. Founder of the Yale Repertory & the American Repertory Theater.

In 2010, he was awarded the National Medal of Arts by President Barack Obama.

I studied under Bob and worked professionally with him during my grad school years at the A.R.T./Harvard. He personally instilled in me the power of storytelling thru an artist collective and the importance of having a strong vision. 

Thank you for your passion, inspiration and guidance. 

“The primary function of a theatre is not to please itself, or even to please its audience. It is to serve talent.” - #RobertBrustein
